{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477847"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14880"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14880"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.02,0.01,0.14,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59151"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7571"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14880"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44562"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2468"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44223"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59151"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with concerns about poor growth and delayed development. He has become increasingly irritable and tired over the past six months. He was born at term and met early developmental milestones, but his walking has become unsteady, and his speech has regressed. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His diet includes meat and dairy products.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale and irritable. His vital signs are within normal limits. His weight and height are below the third percentile. He has an unsteady gait and decreased muscle tone. Investigations reveal haemoglobin 85 g/L (110-140), mean corpuscular volume 102 fL (75-87), vitamin B12 98 pmol/L (150-700), folate 22 nmol/L (7-45), and intrinsic factor antibodies are positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intramuscular vitamin B12","Dietary modification alone","Oral iron supplementation","Oral vitamin B12 supplementation","Oral folate supplementation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features of vitamin B12 deficiency including failure to thrive, developmental regression, and neurological symptoms. The presence of macrocytic anaemia (elevated mean corpuscular volume) and low vitamin B12 levels confirms the diagnosis. The positive intrinsic factor antibodies indicate pernicious anaemia as the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular vitamin B12\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment as it bypasses the gastrointestinal absorption issues caused by intrinsic factor deficiency. In children with severe deficiency and neurological symptoms, rapid replacement is crucial to prevent permanent neurological damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral vitamin B12 supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E would be ineffective in this case due to the inability to absorb vitamin B12 through the gastrointestinal tract in the absence of intrinsic factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral iron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying vitamin B12 deficiency. While the patient is anaemic, it is macrocytic rather than microcytic, indicating that iron deficiency is not the primary issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDietary modification alone\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient as this child\u0027s diet already includes adequate sources of vitamin B12. The problem is absorption rather than intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral folate supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying vitamin B12 deficiency and could potentially mask the haematological manifestations while allowing neurological damage to progress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial treatment with intramuscular vitamin B12, the child will require lifelong replacement therapy. Regular monitoring of vitamin B12 levels, complete blood count, and neurological status is essential. Family screening for pernicious anaemia may also be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin B12 deficiency in children can present with failure to thrive, developmental delay, and neurological symptoms.","Pernicious anaemia should be considered in children with vitamin B12 deficiency, even without a family history.","Early recognition and treatment of vitamin B12 deficiency is crucial to prevent irreversible neurological damage."],"references":["Elgormus Y, Okuyan O, Dumur S, Sayili U, Uzun H. The Epidemiology of Deficiency of Vitamin B12 in Preschool Children in Turkey. Medicina (Kaunas). 2023 Oct 11;59(10):1809. doi: 10.3390/medicina59101809. PMID: 37893527; PMCID: PMC10608353."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44562"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14880"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44562"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-